Showy milkweed is a member of the milkweed family 
Asclepiadaceae (now placed in Apocynaceae, the 
dogbane family).  Showy milkweed is a native herbaceous 
perennial from widespread rhizomes, which produce 
stems that grow to 1½ to 5 ft tall in summer.  The gray-
green leaves are opposite, 4 to 7 inches long, oval, and 
covered in velvety hairs.  Stems and foliage exude milky 
latex sap when cut.  Flowers are in loose clusters at the 
top of the stems and are rose-purple, aging to yellow.  
Individual Asclepias flowers look like crowns, with the 
corolla (petals) reflexed, and hoods above the corolla.  
Plants flower from May to September.  Thick seed pods 3 
to 5 inches long split down one side in fall to release 
reddish-brown, flat seeds.  Each seed has a tuft of white, 
silky hairs that allows them to be dispersed by wind. 
Showy milkweed grows in well-drained soil in full or 
nearly full sun, in pastures, meadows, forest clearings, 
untilled fields, roadsides, and ditch banks, from sea level 
to 6,250 ft.  For updated distribution, please consult the 
Plant Profile for this species on the PLANTS Web site. 
 
