American hornbeam is planted in landscapes and 
naturalized areas.  It prefers deep, fertile, moist, 
acidic soil and grows best in partial shade, but will 
grow in full sun.  Its chief liabilities in cultivation are 
a relatively slow growth rate and difficulty in 
transplantation.  It is not drought-tolerant. 
 
Seeds, buds, or catkins are eaten by a number of 
songbirds, ruffed grouse, ring-necked pheasants, 
bobwhite, turkey, fox, and gray squirrels.  
Cottontails, beaver, and white-tailed deer eat the 
leaves, twigs, and larger stems.  American hornbeam 
is heavily used by beaver, because it is readily 
available in typical beaver habitat. 
 
