erect, long lived, perennial herb that grows one to 
three feet in height, and produces a woody rhizome.  
It has a very distinctive flower with reddish-purple 
petals.  The petals may be pink or white in some rare 
instances.  There is a characteristic “cone” at the 
center of the flower, from which its name is derived.  
Echinacea is rooted in the Greek word for hedge hog, 
echinos, in reference to the spiky appearance of the 
cone.  The stems are rough and have small hairs 
along their entire length.  The leaves are alternate, 
                                                           
