UPDATE usda_plants SET fs_EnvironmentalConcerns='Snake River wheatgrass is long lived and spreads 
primarily via seed distribution.  It is not considered a 
&quot.weedy&quot. or invasive species, but can spread into 
adjoining vegetative communities under ideal 
climatic and environmental conditions.  Most 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
seedings do not spread from original plantings.  It is a 
cross pollinating species and is known to cross with 
bluebunch wheatgrass, thickspike wheatgrass, 
quackgrass and bottlebrush squirreltail.  These 
crosses broaden the gene pool and do not generally 
dominate a site or crowd out the native ecotype and 
in many cases are sterile. 
