seed is extremely fine, requiring mechanical seeding 
equipment to have small seed attachments.  If seeded 
with a ‘hand’ cyclone seeder, the lovegrass seed 
should be mixed with a diluent or a carrier (cornmeal, 
sand, or fine sawdust) for uniform distribution of 
seed.  Do not cover seed more than 1/2 to 1 inch on 
sandy soils. 1/4 inch is sufficient on silt loams.  
Cultipacking soil before seeding is helpful. 
Sites too steep or stony for use of mechanical 
equipment can be seeded without soil scarification.  
Broadcast seeding by air or use of hydroseeders is 
successful if seeding rates are increased to 
compensate for poor seedbed. Where possible, the 
soil should be scarified and firmed. 
Normally, weeping lovegrass can be planted after 
danger of severe frost is over, and anytime 
throughout the summer with success.  Lime and 
fertilizer needs are similar to that for tall fescue and 
ryegrass when used for temporary cover. 
