ALTER TABLE usda_plants ADD fs_ TEXT;
UPDATE usda_plants SET fs_='Description and Adaptation 
 General: Dotted gayfeather belongs to the composite 
or sunflower family (Asteraceae). Dotted gayfeather 
is a native, perennial species that is 1 to 2.5 feet tall 
with one to many stems arising from a woody crown. 
It has a deep tap root which extends up to 7 feet in 
heavy clay soils and to 16 feet in lighter soils. Strong 
lateral roots branch in the first three feet, but they all 
penetrate deeply and most absorptive rootlets are at 
the deeper levels. Its leaves are alternately arranged 
on the stem, are closely spaced and linear, being up 
to six inches long and ¼ inch wide. The leaves are 
dark green with a light colored midrib and covered 
with translucent glandular dots. Dotted gayfeather 
leaves arch upward, have ciliate or hairy margins and 
get progressively shorter the closer they get to the 
stem apex. A dense spike up to a foot long at the end 
 
Alan Shadow, East Texas PMC, Nacogdoches, Texas.  
 
