approximately 90% survival.  Its stolons make this 
grass well adapted to this method of reproduction.  
Larger vegetative clumps of longtom paspalum can 
also be moved to new sites.  Once established, the 
plants will spread themselves via many runners. 
Adequate irrigation must be provided for cuttings or 
clumps to be transplanted successfully. 
Management 
For seed production purposes, longtom paspalum 
must be irrigated when rainfall totals are low or else 
seed production, fill, and fertility will be greatly 
reduced.  Regular fertilization of longtom paspalum 
is also necessary, as it appears to be sensitive to iron 
deficient soils. 
Pests and Potential Problems 
For Texas, this grass is best suited to southern coastal 
areas where mesic conditions dominate, and the 
chance of frost is low.  This grass prefers “wet feet” 
and is not exceedingly drought tolerant.  Under 
drought conditions, it does not compete well with 
bermuda grass.  Weed control and iron deficiency can 
also be a problem. 
For additional assistance regarding the production 
and establishment of longtom paspalum, please 
contact the Plant Material Center at (361) 595-1313. 
