SEASHORE 
PASPALUM 
Panicum vaginatum Sw. 
Plant Symbol = PAVA 
 
Contributed by:  USDA NRCS East Texas Plant 
Materials Center  
 
Seashore paspalum forms dense sod if mowed to a 
one inch height and makes an attractive turf grass.  It 
will withstand traffic well, and has been successfully 
used on golf courses.  Some varieties have a two 
toned appearance to their leaf surfaces which create 
an attractive striped effect when mowed.  Because of 
its salt tolerance, this species can be used 
successfully in areas with saline soils or groundwater.    
  
Conservation: 
Seashore paspalum makes an excellent shoreline 
protector.  It spreads rapidly, forming dense stands 
that anchor soil particles and dissipate wave energy.  
It is easy to establish, and can withstand moderately 
high salinity and brief inundation.  It can also uptake 
heavy metals, and is a candidate as a buffer or filter 
strip plant for Phytoremediation of such substances.        
 
