UPDATE usda_plants SET fs_Description='Pinus palustris P. Mill., longleaf pine, is found in the 
Atlantic and Gulf coastal plains from southeastern 
Virginia to central Florida and west to eastern Texas, 
and in the Piedmont region and Valley and Ridge 
province of Georgia and Alabama.  Longleaf pine is a 
long-lived, native, evergreen conifer with scaly bark.  
Needles are in bundles of 3. they are shiny, dark 
green, and 8 to 15 inches long.  Cones are 6 to 8 
inches long.  Mature trees attain a height of 100 to 
120 feet and 2½ feet in diameter.  Its seeds are the 
largest of all southern pines.  It has extensive lateral 
roots and a taproot that grows 8 to 12 feet long. 
