American elder grows best in full sunlight.  Once 
established, elders soon outdistance herbaceous 
competition.  Thickets of elder are replaced by more 
shade-tolerant species during the later stages of forest 
succession, but individual plants and small runners 
will persist under a forest canopy. 
 
American elder is distributed primarily throughout 
the eastern and midwestern United States.  For a 
current distribution map, please consult the Plant 
