S. virginicus is commonly found in coastal dune 
habitats and it does best if sea water level fluctuates 
from 2 inches above soil surface to 6 inches below.  
It also does well in a variety of different soils from 
clays to sands.    Being a plant that is adapted to low 
rainfall and high salinity, S. virginicus is fairly wide 
spread throughout the tropical regions and is native to 
the Pacific Islands Region as well as the continental 
United States.  It also occurs in Africa, western 
seaboard of India, Sri Lanka, and Australia. 
